
00:00:00,800 --> 00:00:02,550
(man) The sharks are back,

00:00:02,550 --> 00:00:03,820
in an all-new season
of "Shark Tank,"

00:00:03,820 --> 00:00:06,870
where hopeful entrepreneurs
from across the country

00:00:06,870 --> 00:00:09,650
dream of a chance
to secure an investment

00:00:09,650 --> 00:00:11,570
and gain powerful partners

00:00:11,570 --> 00:00:14,870
to start, grow,
or save their businesses.

00:00:14,870 --> 00:00:16,930
I'm not trying to make friends.
I'm trying to make money.

00:00:16,930 --> 00:00:19,550
We can dramatically
increase profit.

00:00:19,550 --> 00:00:21,700
If the sharks
hear a great idea,

00:00:21,700 --> 00:00:23,550
they're ready to invest

00:00:23,550 --> 00:00:25,800
using their own money.
They're so greedy.

00:00:25,800 --> 00:00:28,580
And they'll fight each other
for a piece of the action.

00:00:28,580 --> 00:00:30,700
I feel this Barbara crap.

00:00:30,700 --> 00:00:31,970
I've worked with him.
He's miserable.

00:00:31,970 --> 00:00:34,920
You're a vicious granny.
I'm not vicious at all.

00:00:34,920 --> 00:00:38,550
But first, the entrepreneurs
must convince a shark

00:00:38,550 --> 00:00:40,830
to invest the full amount
they're asking for,

00:00:40,830 --> 00:00:42,800
or they'll walk away
with nothing.

00:00:42,800 --> 00:00:43,930
I don't think
you have a clue

00:00:43,930 --> 00:00:46,700
about what you're going to do
to run your business.

00:00:46,700 --> 00:00:48,020
You have no business concept.

00:00:48,020 --> 00:00:50,620
It's sink...
you're getting your ass
kicked in here.

00:00:50,620 --> 00:00:52,680
Or swim.
Any side effect?

00:00:52,680 --> 00:00:54,550
Diarrhea.
Ooh!

00:00:54,550 --> 00:00:55,880
Ha!
You guys don't make it easy,
do you?

00:00:55,880 --> 00:00:57,980
Welcome to the "Shark Tank."

00:00:57,980 --> 00:00:59,030
♪♪♪

00:00:59,030 --> 00:01:01,650
Who are the sharks?

00:01:01,650 --> 00:01:05,820
They're self-made millionaire
and billionaire investors

00:01:05,820 --> 00:01:07,920
who are entrepreneurs
themselves.

00:01:09,650 --> 00:01:11,980
Kevin O'Leary
is a venture capitalist

00:01:11,980 --> 00:01:15,580
who turned a $10,000 loan
into a software business

00:01:15,580 --> 00:01:18,650
worth $4.2 billion.

00:01:20,700 --> 00:01:22,500
Barbara Corcoran went
from working

00:01:22,500 --> 00:01:24,300
as a waitress in Manhattan

00:01:24,300 --> 00:01:27,600
to building the city's
preeminent real estate empire.

00:01:27,600 --> 00:01:30,700
Daymond John is a fashion mogul
and branding expert

00:01:30,700 --> 00:01:33,220
Who grew
his homemade clothing line

00:01:33,220 --> 00:01:36,670
into the globally recognized
fashion brand Fubu.

00:01:36,670 --> 00:01:40,270
Robert Herjavec, the son
of an immigrant factory worker,

00:01:40,270 --> 00:01:42,270
is now a technology mogul

00:01:42,270 --> 00:01:43,700
who sold his first
internet companies

00:01:43,700 --> 00:01:47,400
for over $350 million.

00:01:47,400 --> 00:01:49,420
And Mark Cuban,

00:01:49,420 --> 00:01:52,340
notorious
billionaire entrepreneur

00:01:52,340 --> 00:01:55,233
and the outspoken owner
of the Dallas Mavericks.

00:02:04,300 --> 00:02:06,200
(man)
First in is Drew Beaumier,

00:02:06,200 --> 00:02:10,100
with his idea of the next
generation of costumes.

00:02:10,100 --> 00:02:12,070
Oh, lord.
Are they people?

00:02:12,070 --> 00:02:15,300
(whirring)

00:02:17,300 --> 00:02:20,020
HA!

00:02:20,020 --> 00:02:21,300
Ooh!

00:02:28,150 --> 00:02:30,370
Hello, sharks.
My name is Drew Beaumier.

00:02:30,370 --> 00:02:32,270
My product is drive suits,

00:02:32,270 --> 00:02:35,020
and I'm requesting $150,000

00:02:35,020 --> 00:02:37,330
for 20% equity stake
in my company.

00:02:37,330 --> 00:02:39,420
Drive suits are
the first generation

00:02:39,420 --> 00:02:41,320
of wearable
recreational devices

00:02:41,320 --> 00:02:43,270
and are unlike any other
product available

00:02:43,270 --> 00:02:45,030
on the market today.

00:02:45,030 --> 00:02:47,120
Their main attraction
is the function

00:02:47,120 --> 00:02:49,470
to instantaneously
transform the user

00:02:49,470 --> 00:02:51,470
from a human or walking state

00:02:51,470 --> 00:02:54,330
to a vehicular
or motor-driven form.

00:02:54,330 --> 00:02:57,200
(laughs)
Crazy.

00:02:57,200 --> 00:02:59,350
Whether I'm
at a national convention

00:02:59,350 --> 00:03:02,170
or simply testing a prototype
out on the street,

00:03:02,170 --> 00:03:03,470
everyone stops,
and the first thing

00:03:03,470 --> 00:03:06,380
they always ask me is,
"where can I get one?"

00:03:06,380 --> 00:03:08,050
This leads me to believe

00:03:08,050 --> 00:03:10,070
that the highest financial
payoff for my invention

00:03:10,070 --> 00:03:12,370
exists in mass manufacturing
and distribution.

00:03:12,370 --> 00:03:14,380
With your much-needed
investment

00:03:14,380 --> 00:03:17,030
and equally needed and respected
business expertise,

00:03:17,030 --> 00:03:19,150
I see absolutely no reason
why together

00:03:19,150 --> 00:03:21,330
we can't mark a new standard
in children's entertainment

00:03:21,330 --> 00:03:23,120
and create a product
that literally

00:03:23,120 --> 00:03:24,350
drives off the shelves.

00:03:24,350 --> 00:03:28,350
(whirring)

00:03:28,350 --> 00:03:31,280
That's cool.
(laughs)

00:03:31,280 --> 00:03:34,180
Thank you very much.

00:03:34,180 --> 00:03:35,300
How fast does it go?

00:03:35,300 --> 00:03:37,420
It goes about 10, uh,
maybe 12 miles an hour.

00:03:37,420 --> 00:03:39,470
Drew, can I see it? Can I--
absolutely.

00:03:39,470 --> 00:03:42,000
(Barbara) Drew, how did you
come up with the idea?

00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:44,450
Um, just basically I needed
to make my rent money,

00:03:44,450 --> 00:03:46,180
and I just kind of had
this idea.

00:03:46,180 --> 00:03:47,400
I saw a flier
for a costume contest.

00:03:47,400 --> 00:03:50,320
And I saw a chance to, like,
definitely make my money back,

00:03:50,320 --> 00:03:52,400
my investment back,
even if it was just

00:03:52,400 --> 00:03:55,400
selling the costume
after I created it.

00:03:55,400 --> 00:03:57,130
Can I ask you a question?
I'm sorry.
Absolutely.

00:03:57,130 --> 00:03:59,030
So... I get you put it on.
Mm-Hmm.

00:03:59,030 --> 00:04:00,220
Then how do you go?

00:04:00,220 --> 00:04:02,020
It's a hand switch.
(whirs)

00:04:02,020 --> 00:04:03,180
OHH!

00:04:03,180 --> 00:04:04,270
(laughs)

00:04:04,270 --> 00:04:05,450
Oh, that's cool.
And it's--

00:04:05,450 --> 00:04:07,370
I know it's mechanical
and technological-Looking,

00:04:07,370 --> 00:04:10,000
but honestly, all it is
is a positive/negative wire

00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:11,250
to a battery with a switch.

00:04:11,250 --> 00:04:12,450
Is that insurable?

00:04:12,450 --> 00:04:14,220
I actually think these
are safer

00:04:14,220 --> 00:04:16,250
than most, uh, like,
standing apparatuses.

00:04:16,250 --> 00:04:17,420
Because you're so close
to the ground,

00:04:17,420 --> 00:04:19,170
you can't fall, yeah.

00:04:19,170 --> 00:04:22,250
How big is the box
that you ship this in?

00:04:22,250 --> 00:04:24,180
I have not, uh, yet
begun selling them.

00:04:24,180 --> 00:04:27,270
♪♪♪

00:04:27,270 --> 00:04:29,450
I was pretty much advised
to not sell

00:04:29,450 --> 00:04:33,080
until I had everything
covered with patenting.

00:04:33,080 --> 00:04:35,420
What do you want
the $150,000 for?

00:04:35,420 --> 00:04:37,220
I believe that's
the minimal amount

00:04:37,220 --> 00:04:39,380
I would need to bring
my product to the next level,

00:04:39,380 --> 00:04:41,480
which is basically having
an autocad drawing,

00:04:41,480 --> 00:04:45,320
all patents, and getting
a manufacturer's request.

00:04:45,320 --> 00:04:47,150
Tell us about what it takes
to build one--

00:04:47,150 --> 00:04:50,150
You know, what the pieces are,
and then also go into

00:04:50,150 --> 00:04:52,170
the patents you're trying
to put together.

00:04:52,170 --> 00:04:54,480
They're basically made out
of currently successful

00:04:54,480 --> 00:04:56,230
children's products and toys.

00:04:56,230 --> 00:04:58,400
Have you been to toy fair yet?
I haven't.

00:04:58,400 --> 00:05:01,000
I-I mostly work in, like,
costume contests

00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:03,130
And, uh, performances
and appearances.

00:05:03,130 --> 00:05:05,330
In the past two years,
we've won about five contests

00:05:05,330 --> 00:05:08,200
and I made about $25,000
in cash and prizes.

00:05:09,430 --> 00:05:11,430
But, Drew, isn't it time,
at this point,

00:05:11,430 --> 00:05:15,000
to partner with
one of the big toy companies,

00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:18,030
because so much of the challenge
you face is manufacturing,

00:05:18,030 --> 00:05:19,150
which they have nailed down,

00:05:19,150 --> 00:05:20,470
and more importantly,
distribution?

00:05:20,470 --> 00:05:23,320
What you're wearing
could probably be dumbed down

00:05:23,320 --> 00:05:25,400
to a $99 price point,
I would hope,

00:05:25,400 --> 00:05:27,220
and perhaps packaged in a way

00:05:27,220 --> 00:05:29,080
that would fit on the shelves
of walmart.

00:05:29,080 --> 00:05:31,350
If you had... a partner.

00:05:33,170 --> 00:05:35,170
(Robert) But what's proprietary
about it, Kevin?

00:05:35,170 --> 00:05:37,000
Like, he goes
to a toy company.

00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:39,280
Wh-What's unique?
What can't they copy?

00:05:39,280 --> 00:05:42,170
Basically, what I have to
bring to the table for them

00:05:42,170 --> 00:05:44,300
is just the trial and error
over the past two years.

00:05:44,300 --> 00:05:47,220
These are definitely not
the first prototypes.

00:05:47,220 --> 00:05:49,100
So it's your experience?
Yes.

00:05:49,100 --> 00:05:50,220
The best thing I have in place

00:05:50,220 --> 00:05:51,380
is I have the trademark
for drive suits.

00:05:51,380 --> 00:05:53,150
I have not been able
to afford a patent.

00:05:53,150 --> 00:05:54,420
I had a provisional patent,
which expired,

00:05:54,420 --> 00:05:56,100
but I didn't see it doing
much good.

00:05:57,450 --> 00:05:59,380
Whoa. Don't like that.

00:06:01,270 --> 00:06:02,470
You know what?

00:06:02,470 --> 00:06:04,470
These guys are wasting time.

00:06:04,470 --> 00:06:07,080
I call these guys hammerheads,
'cause they think

00:06:07,080 --> 00:06:09,330
that everything that
walks in the door is a nail,

00:06:09,330 --> 00:06:11,200
and they just try
to pound 'em.

00:06:11,200 --> 00:06:13,330
Because it works, Mark,
that's why.
You--It doesn't work.

00:06:13,330 --> 00:06:15,300
You guys--You guys aren't
about--look.

00:06:15,300 --> 00:06:17,400
You guys aren't about
a product yet. So you've got--
what are they about?

00:06:17,400 --> 00:06:19,080
You guys have gone

00:06:19,080 --> 00:06:21,030
and you've won all this money
at costume parties.

00:06:21,030 --> 00:06:22,380
Tell me how much money
you've made,

00:06:22,380 --> 00:06:24,230
what you've been
hired to do.

00:06:24,230 --> 00:06:26,020
My daily rate is usually--
for a costume,

00:06:26,020 --> 00:06:28,270
for an 8-hour day, is I usually
charge $300 or $400.

00:06:28,270 --> 00:06:29,400
That's it?
Oh, my gosh.
That's...

00:06:29,400 --> 00:06:31,080
that's nothing.
Way too low.

00:06:32,120 --> 00:06:33,370
Wha-What is it you want?

00:06:33,370 --> 00:06:35,050
You want to be a circus
performer, or you want to sell

00:06:35,050 --> 00:06:36,480
500,000 units
through the toy chains?

00:06:36,480 --> 00:06:38,280
That's what I would
like to do.

00:06:38,280 --> 00:06:41,120
Like I said, I'd much rather
mass manufacture them and--

00:06:41,120 --> 00:06:43,320
Okay, so you need
a partner to do that.

00:06:43,320 --> 00:06:45,020
Absolutely.

00:06:45,020 --> 00:06:47,230
So why wouldn't you
take this to a toy company,

00:06:47,230 --> 00:06:48,450
partner with them?

00:06:48,450 --> 00:06:51,050
They're currently paying
between 5% and 7% in royalties.

00:06:51,050 --> 00:06:53,330
You'd make some money,
my friend.
Sir.

00:06:53,330 --> 00:06:55,200
(Mark) what they're really
gonna say is,

00:06:55,200 --> 00:06:56,400
"It's not quite ready.

00:06:56,400 --> 00:06:58,420
"We're not gonna pay you
7% of anything right now,

00:06:58,420 --> 00:07:00,130
"because there's nothing
to pay.

00:07:00,130 --> 00:07:01,330
"We're not gonna pay you
an upfront fee.

00:07:01,330 --> 00:07:03,170
"and, oh, by the way,
even if we like it,

00:07:03,170 --> 00:07:05,280
we're gonna take six months
to put together a contract,"

00:07:05,280 --> 00:07:07,180
and meanwhile you're
sitting around doing nothing.

00:07:07,180 --> 00:07:09,030
So, Mark, you want to send
this guy into a destiny

00:07:09,030 --> 00:07:10,180
of being a circus performer?

00:07:12,130 --> 00:07:14,120
(Robert)
Here--Here's my challenge.

00:07:14,120 --> 00:07:16,000
You want to manufacture these.

00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:18,250
As we've decided,
this is one of the rare times

00:07:18,250 --> 00:07:20,000
I think unless you have
a patent

00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:22,070
or some proprietary
technology,

00:07:22,070 --> 00:07:24,030
you're gonna be in trouble.

00:07:24,030 --> 00:07:25,300
I'm out.

00:07:25,300 --> 00:07:28,000
Thank you.

00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:31,020
So, Drew, it's just
so soon for me,

00:07:31,020 --> 00:07:33,300
because there's so many
mysteries right now

00:07:33,300 --> 00:07:35,270
with how much it's gonna cost,
where you're gonna make it,

00:07:35,270 --> 00:07:37,430
how you're gonna ship it.

00:07:37,430 --> 00:07:40,130
I'm sorry, but I'm out.

00:07:40,130 --> 00:07:41,380
Okay.

00:07:44,250 --> 00:07:47,380
I'm very concerned about
the liability issue,

00:07:47,380 --> 00:07:49,480
because I have kids,
and seeing my kids

00:07:49,480 --> 00:07:51,250
on the streets with this,

00:07:51,250 --> 00:07:53,270
I think I'd be
sick with worry, honestly.

00:07:54,430 --> 00:07:56,380
For that reason, I'm out.

00:07:56,380 --> 00:07:58,420
Thank you.

00:08:00,150 --> 00:08:02,470
Three sharks are out.

00:08:02,470 --> 00:08:08,020
Mark and Kevin are
drew's last chance at a deal.

00:08:08,020 --> 00:08:10,400
I like the business.
I'm gonna make you an offer.

00:08:12,080 --> 00:08:14,100
Using this $150,000,

00:08:14,100 --> 00:08:15,380
we're gonna make
20 of these.

00:08:15,380 --> 00:08:17,200
Okay.

00:08:17,200 --> 00:08:18,320
And then we'll work
with costume designers

00:08:18,320 --> 00:08:20,000
to create different looks.

00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:21,250
And we'll go out
and we'll have some fun,

00:08:21,250 --> 00:08:22,370
and we'll make it viral,
we'll put it online.

00:08:22,370 --> 00:08:25,020
(groans)
We'll also hire
an engineer

00:08:25,020 --> 00:08:27,180
to help you optimize
the design of this.

00:08:27,180 --> 00:08:30,270
We'll see where we can take it
in terms of cost.

00:08:30,270 --> 00:08:33,050
Then we'll make some
business decisions.

00:08:33,050 --> 00:08:34,470
Because the key here,
you have to understand--

00:08:34,470 --> 00:08:36,120
You're not a company yet.

00:08:36,120 --> 00:08:38,050
(Daymond) So, Cuban wants you
to work for him

00:08:38,050 --> 00:08:40,030
and suck your blood
for about three years...

00:08:40,030 --> 00:08:41,450
(Barbara laughs)
Until maybe there's, uh...

00:08:41,450 --> 00:08:43,130
that's true.
Some kind of commercial use,
and then he'll--

00:08:43,130 --> 00:08:44,280
No, that's not--
That's so far from the truth.

00:08:44,280 --> 00:08:46,130
As an elephant in a circus.

00:08:47,450 --> 00:08:49,230
You might get a feed bag.

00:08:49,230 --> 00:08:51,480
No. That's so far from
the truth, and you know it.

00:08:51,480 --> 00:08:54,080
So if we can agree that
there's some uncertainty

00:08:54,080 --> 00:08:55,270
and we'll learn as we go

00:08:55,270 --> 00:08:57,220
and we'll make some
business decisions as we go,

00:08:57,220 --> 00:09:00,030
then I'll offer you
$150,000 in cash

00:09:00,030 --> 00:09:02,050
for 40% of the company.

00:09:05,430 --> 00:09:07,270
Thank you very much
for your offer.

00:09:09,050 --> 00:09:10,280
I don't like to think
small like that.

00:09:10,280 --> 00:09:12,450
I don't want to put you
in a circus with a cattle prod

00:09:12,450 --> 00:09:14,070
and keep blasting you.
(laughs)

00:09:15,100 --> 00:09:16,320
I want to go big.
I think big.

00:09:16,320 --> 00:09:17,330
Okay.

00:09:17,330 --> 00:09:19,420
I would give you $150,000

00:09:19,420 --> 00:09:23,300
for 30% of the company,
with one contingency--

00:09:23,300 --> 00:09:25,080
I bring it to the toy company.

00:09:25,080 --> 00:09:27,030
They're either gonna love it
or they're gonna hate it.

00:09:27,030 --> 00:09:28,400
So the risk you've got
with my deal is,

00:09:28,400 --> 00:09:31,070
they simply don't think
there's an opportunity for it.

00:09:31,070 --> 00:09:33,430
You know, I sold my company
to a toy company.

00:09:33,430 --> 00:09:35,300
I know all the toy company
C.E.O.S.

00:09:35,300 --> 00:09:37,420
Look, Drew, two things
that are absolute.

00:09:37,420 --> 00:09:40,270
One--With my deal,
you have cash in hand.

00:09:40,270 --> 00:09:42,250
Period, end of story.

00:09:42,250 --> 00:09:45,200
Two--there's no toy company
that won't take my call.

00:09:45,200 --> 00:09:47,250
Question--is that
the right thing to do?

00:09:47,250 --> 00:09:49,370
I mean, there's no question
mine's the better offer.

00:09:49,370 --> 00:09:51,220
You're either gonna be
an elephant

00:09:51,220 --> 00:09:53,480
or you're gonna be rich.

00:09:53,480 --> 00:09:56,380
You have two paths.
What are you going to do?

00:09:56,380 --> 00:10:01,030
♪♪♪

00:10:05,180 --> 00:10:08,230
Drew has two offers
on the table--

00:10:08,230 --> 00:10:13,020
$150,000 for 40% of his company
from Mark Cuban.

00:10:13,020 --> 00:10:17,280
Kevin's offer is $150,000
for 30%,

00:10:17,280 --> 00:10:22,080
contingent on a deal
with a toy company.

00:10:22,080 --> 00:10:25,120
♪♪♪

00:10:25,120 --> 00:10:27,370
(Kevin) Drew,
isn't it time at this point

00:10:27,370 --> 00:10:30,250
to partner with one
of the big toy companies?

00:10:30,250 --> 00:10:32,020
We'll either get a deal or not.

00:10:32,020 --> 00:10:33,280
The beauty is,
I know how to negotiate it,

00:10:33,280 --> 00:10:35,330
and you will either be
in a partnership

00:10:35,330 --> 00:10:37,320
with a toy company right away,
or you won't be.

00:10:37,320 --> 00:10:39,270
And you'll either be
very rich,

00:10:39,270 --> 00:10:41,250
or you'll work for Mark
as an elephant.

00:10:42,400 --> 00:10:45,170
Look, Drew, the idea
of trying to sell

00:10:45,170 --> 00:10:47,020
to toy manufacturers
is ridiculous.

00:10:47,020 --> 00:10:48,350
You don't want it to go
to license to them.

