00:33:27,030 --> 00:33:28,950
Yeah. Then there can be...
(laughs)

00:33:28,950 --> 00:33:31,400
a little tummy distress--
If you ate the whole tin.

00:33:31,400 --> 00:33:33,130
Tummy distress?

00:33:33,130 --> 00:33:35,210
What would that be?
Diarrhea.

00:33:37,380 --> 00:33:39,310
(Daymond and Barbara) Oh.
Oh.

00:33:39,310 --> 00:33:41,230
(laughing)
(Daymond) It's not
like a laxative.

00:33:41,230 --> 00:33:43,960
I'm just trying to get
clarity.
Oh, no, no, no.
Not like a laxative.

00:33:43,960 --> 00:33:45,360
All right, you guys can
continue to eat them then.

00:33:45,360 --> 00:33:47,410
You're a couple of grannies
on steroids. I get it.

00:33:47,410 --> 00:33:49,980
(laughing)
You're valuing

00:33:49,980 --> 00:33:52,280
your ice chips business

00:33:52,280 --> 00:33:54,950
at $1.67 million.

00:33:54,950 --> 00:33:56,160
Yes.
That's quite a bit.

00:33:56,160 --> 00:33:58,260
Explain to me why you think
it's worth that much money.

00:34:00,160 --> 00:34:02,210
This year,
up through Friday,

00:34:02,210 --> 00:34:06,280
our sales for ice chips
was $342,000.

00:34:07,410 --> 00:34:08,950
Really?
Yes.

00:34:08,950 --> 00:34:13,000
Last year,
sales were $360,000.

00:34:13,000 --> 00:34:14,430
Wow. Charlotte,
that's fantastic.

00:34:14,430 --> 00:34:16,200
Sales--
So we've almost doubled.

00:34:16,200 --> 00:34:18,160
Oh, so you're halfway through.
Yes.

00:34:18,160 --> 00:34:20,950
So you think you'll hit,
uh, $700,000 this year.
$700,000.

00:34:20,950 --> 00:34:22,150
We actually think
we could hit

00:34:22,150 --> 00:34:24,110
that million-Dollar mark
by the end of the year.

00:34:24,110 --> 00:34:26,400
Those are some sweet numbers.
(both laugh)

00:34:26,400 --> 00:34:29,360
What are you making it for
and what are you selling it for?

00:34:29,360 --> 00:34:32,310
We make it right now
for $1.11 a tin.

00:34:32,310 --> 00:34:36,080
It wholesales for
$3 and 12 1/2 cents a tin.

00:34:36,080 --> 00:34:37,250
(Daymond) nice.

00:34:37,250 --> 00:34:40,150
The average sale
in a store is $5.

00:34:40,150 --> 00:34:42,150
Are you opening more accounts,

00:34:42,150 --> 00:34:45,250
or are the same accounts
just increasing their orders?

00:34:45,250 --> 00:34:47,030
Yes and Yes.

00:34:47,030 --> 00:34:49,060
Nice.
We have about
ten new accounts--

00:34:49,060 --> 00:34:51,080
10 to 12 new accounts
every week.

00:34:51,080 --> 00:34:52,400
Why is it shaped like flakes?

00:34:52,400 --> 00:34:54,010
The honest answer?

00:34:56,210 --> 00:34:58,330
No, I want you to lie
to me, granny.
(both laugh)

00:34:58,330 --> 00:35:00,360
Two grannies in a garage
couldn't press out

00:35:00,360 --> 00:35:02,260
100,000 little pellets.

00:35:02,260 --> 00:35:04,000
(Beverly) Yeah.
(Robert) Come on, seriously?

00:35:04,000 --> 00:35:05,250
So you just hit it
with a hammer? Bang?
Serious.

00:35:05,250 --> 00:35:07,030
Yep. Yes.
But they said

00:35:07,030 --> 00:35:09,330
you couldn't make hard candy
from xylitol,

00:35:09,330 --> 00:35:12,130
and we did what they said
couldn't be done.

00:35:12,130 --> 00:35:14,430
And by pouring it
and then breaking it this way

00:35:14,430 --> 00:35:17,410
and calling it ice chips,
everyone has loved it.
(laughs)

00:35:17,410 --> 00:35:20,250
Tell me your background
before you became grannies.

00:35:20,250 --> 00:35:22,110
Well,
I was a romance writer.

00:35:22,110 --> 00:35:25,200
So probably not gonna
help you much.
(laughter)

00:35:25,200 --> 00:35:27,400
I have a bachelor of science
degree in natural health.

00:35:27,400 --> 00:35:29,410
(Daymond) There's other candies
in the market.

00:35:29,410 --> 00:35:31,350
I-I just want to know
about your competitors.

00:35:31,350 --> 00:35:36,100
Spry is our biggest competitor,
'cause dentists also do them.

00:35:36,100 --> 00:35:39,000
But they have
a pressed candy, like...

00:35:39,000 --> 00:35:40,380
what other pressed candy?
Like an altoid?

00:35:40,380 --> 00:35:42,310
Maybe Altoids is pressed.
Yeah. And are these sold

00:35:42,310 --> 00:35:44,430
only in, uh, mainly, uh,
health food stores,

00:35:44,430 --> 00:35:47,180
or are they in 7-Elevens
and Walgreens and...

00:35:47,180 --> 00:35:49,330
Well, that's distribution.
It's hard to get in.

00:35:49,330 --> 00:35:51,110
We do have
a lot of grocery stores.

00:35:51,110 --> 00:35:52,380
We're in grocery--
But there's a distributor

00:35:52,380 --> 00:35:54,210
you want to sell to
that's gonna supply all them.

00:35:54,210 --> 00:35:56,260
(Beverly and Charlotte) Yes.
(Daymond) So you guys--

00:35:56,260 --> 00:35:58,030
You have everything.
You know, you know your market,

00:35:58,030 --> 00:36:00,180
you know your numbers.
You're making money.

00:36:00,180 --> 00:36:03,080
So why are you here?
Automation.

00:36:03,080 --> 00:36:07,110
To bring our margin down
where we make this for 77 cents.

00:36:07,110 --> 00:36:08,400
Basically want us
to buy you a machine

00:36:08,400 --> 00:36:10,380
that's gonna cost
$250,000, right?

00:36:10,380 --> 00:36:12,100
Yes.
Well--

00:36:12,100 --> 00:36:14,330
$250,000--That's not even
$5,000 per grandchild.

00:36:14,330 --> 00:36:17,280
Get those grandchildren
out there working.

00:36:17,280 --> 00:36:19,100
That's true.
Get them to make
a few thousand bucks,

00:36:19,100 --> 00:36:20,350
and you're good to go.
We are.

00:36:20,350 --> 00:36:23,030
We have two of them
working there now.
(both laugh)

00:36:23,030 --> 00:36:24,400
I'd like to make you
an offer.

00:36:24,400 --> 00:36:27,050
What I like best
about the product

00:36:27,050 --> 00:36:29,410
over all of the candy products
I've seen, dietary or not,

00:36:29,410 --> 00:36:33,160
is I love the idea
that you have chips.

00:36:33,160 --> 00:36:35,160
You can pick how big
or little a chip

00:36:35,160 --> 00:36:36,980
you want to pop in your mouth.

00:36:36,980 --> 00:36:38,360
I don't know why, but I love,
like, picking it out.
(laughing)

00:36:38,360 --> 00:36:40,280
Like a choice.
(Mark) Yeah, you're right.

00:36:40,280 --> 00:36:42,410
(Barbara) You know?
That's unique.

00:36:42,410 --> 00:36:46,100
And I would just like
to go on a sales call with you,

00:36:46,100 --> 00:36:48,180
just to see what you do.
You're a hoot.

00:36:48,180 --> 00:36:50,260
(laughing)
So it would be three grandmas.

00:36:50,260 --> 00:36:52,110
Whatever. No problem.
The full granny gang.

00:36:52,110 --> 00:36:54,280
If you wanna call me
a grandma, no problem.

00:36:54,280 --> 00:36:57,100
So I'm gonna give you
half the investment--$125,000.

00:36:57,100 --> 00:36:59,050
But I'll have to have
more stock.

00:36:59,050 --> 00:37:01,400
I would need 1/3 of the business
for that--33%.

00:37:03,380 --> 00:37:05,260
Ohh! That's crazy.

00:37:08,060 --> 00:37:09,200
For just your piece?

00:37:09,200 --> 00:37:10,280
Yes, for just my piece.

00:37:10,280 --> 00:37:11,410
So, Barbara,
they have to go out and raise

00:37:11,410 --> 00:37:15,280
the other $125,000,
and get another 33%.

00:37:15,280 --> 00:37:17,260
You're a vicious granny.

00:37:17,260 --> 00:37:20,260
♪♪♪

00:37:27,000 --> 00:37:29,900
♪♪♪

00:37:29,900 --> 00:37:33,533
Beverly and Charlotte
have one partial offer

00:37:33,533 --> 00:37:35,066
on the table,
from Barbara.

00:37:35,066 --> 00:37:38,046
But she wants
a whopping 33% of the company

00:37:38,046 --> 00:37:39,996
for just her half
of the investment.

00:37:39,996 --> 00:37:43,136
You're a vicious granny.
I-I--
I'm not vicious at all.

00:37:43,136 --> 00:37:45,986
Ladies, what else
is in this candy?

00:37:45,986 --> 00:37:47,266
(Barbara) Hold on. Hold on.
Finish, Barb. Finish, Barb.

00:37:47,266 --> 00:37:49,046
Please, please, please.
(laughs)

00:37:49,046 --> 00:37:51,966
What I guarantee you--
as part of the offer--

00:37:51,966 --> 00:37:54,216
is that I'll get you
in 3,000 big box stores

00:37:54,216 --> 00:37:55,886
to sell your product.

00:37:55,886 --> 00:37:57,866
Ooh. Interesting.
And that's worth
a lot of money.

00:37:57,866 --> 00:37:59,236
Would you feel free
to take out your dentures

00:37:59,236 --> 00:38:01,016
and throw it at her...
(laughing)

00:38:01,016 --> 00:38:03,846
For that rude
and insensitive offer?
What is wrong with that?

00:38:03,846 --> 00:38:05,816
How long would it take you
to get into all those

00:38:05,816 --> 00:38:07,096
big box stores?
Not long.

00:38:10,046 --> 00:38:13,046
Grannies, I want to put
the other half up

00:38:13,046 --> 00:38:15,886
that Barbara needs, and you
get something else from me.

00:38:15,886 --> 00:38:18,136
I'm gonna talk her back
into sanity on value.

00:38:18,136 --> 00:38:19,986
So what I'm gonna say is this--

00:38:19,986 --> 00:38:23,096
I'll put up the other
$125,000,

00:38:23,096 --> 00:38:24,936
and we will each get
20% each.

00:38:24,936 --> 00:38:28,046
So we're taking 40%,
not 66%.

00:38:28,046 --> 00:38:31,046
You know what?
I will retrench a bit

00:38:31,046 --> 00:38:33,136
on that value,
but not with this guy.

00:38:35,886 --> 00:38:37,136
He's no fun to work with.

00:38:37,136 --> 00:38:39,136
He's totally focused
on money,

00:38:39,136 --> 00:38:41,116
and you both know
it's not about the money.
You need somebody

00:38:41,116 --> 00:38:43,266
like Mr. Wonderful
in the model.
Trust me, you don't need him.

00:38:43,266 --> 00:38:45,266
So I'll do that deal. Any other
guys wanna do that deal?

00:38:45,266 --> 00:38:47,066
No problem.
But not with this guy.

00:38:47,066 --> 00:38:51,016
So I'll do $125,000 for 20%,

00:38:51,016 --> 00:38:52,266
because I must say,
I did feel a little bit greedy.

00:38:52,266 --> 00:38:54,136
Look at the value I've
created for you already.

00:38:54,136 --> 00:38:56,046
I took her down
from being insane,

00:38:56,046 --> 00:38:58,146
asking for 66%.

00:38:58,146 --> 00:39:00,966
(Daymond) Well, I'm--I'm--
I'm interested.

00:39:00,966 --> 00:39:03,796
My only concern is
I don't want, uh, you guys

00:39:03,796 --> 00:39:05,136
to be doing the manufacturing.

00:39:05,136 --> 00:39:07,216
I don't want to have to learn
that part of the business.

00:39:07,216 --> 00:39:12,796
So what I'd be interested in
is $250,000 for...

00:39:12,796 --> 00:39:14,246
30%,

00:39:14,246 --> 00:39:17,266
and we go out and take
the manufacturing elsewhere.

00:39:19,166 --> 00:39:21,866
Do we have any other offers?
Solid?

00:39:21,866 --> 00:39:22,986
Patience is a virtue.

00:39:22,986 --> 00:39:24,816
(laughs)
(Daymond)
I'm the only full offer.

00:39:24,816 --> 00:39:26,966
You have half offers
from Kevin and Barbara.

00:39:26,966 --> 00:39:28,946
Well, Barbara doesn't want
to play in this candy box.
And these savages

00:39:28,946 --> 00:39:30,836
want to take 40%
of your company.

00:39:30,836 --> 00:39:32,866
I-I delivered so much value
to the grannies,

00:39:32,866 --> 00:39:35,036
and I'm getting nothing for it.
I'm really heartbroken.

00:39:35,036 --> 00:39:36,936
We're smiling at you pretty,
if that helps. (laughs)

00:39:36,936 --> 00:39:39,866
It helps.

00:39:39,866 --> 00:39:41,116
I'm interested in working
with Barbara,

00:39:41,116 --> 00:39:44,046
because I think she works really
well with consumer products.

00:39:44,046 --> 00:39:47,916
I see a lot of ways
that we can work together.

00:39:47,916 --> 00:39:49,886
So I'm happy to go in
with Barbara

00:39:49,886 --> 00:39:52,286
at $125k for 20%,

00:39:52,286 --> 00:39:54,196
and $125k for 20%.

00:39:54,196 --> 00:39:56,286
You know, when I put out
my offer,

00:39:56,286 --> 00:39:58,146
I was hoping
Mark would jump in with me.

00:39:58,146 --> 00:40:00,186
There's no better partner here.

00:40:00,186 --> 00:40:02,036
(inhales)
Ladies, it--

00:40:02,036 --> 00:40:05,186
It's sweeter than I would
have offered you.

00:40:05,186 --> 00:40:06,996
I'm out.

00:40:08,046 --> 00:40:09,216
Thank you.

00:40:09,216 --> 00:40:11,146
Okay, grannies,
let's shake it up a bit.

00:40:11,146 --> 00:40:12,986
I want back in this deal.

00:40:16,886 --> 00:40:18,886
Okay, so here's what
I'm gonna propose.

00:40:18,886 --> 00:40:20,096
I want to join Daymond.

00:40:20,096 --> 00:40:22,046
So he'll put up $125,000.

00:40:22,046 --> 00:40:25,836
I'll put up $125,000.
So you get your $250,000.

00:40:25,836 --> 00:40:29,036
But I want to be part
of a 35% deal.

00:40:29,036 --> 00:40:30,086
All right?

00:40:30,086 --> 00:40:31,996
But you get two sharks.

00:40:31,996 --> 00:40:33,886
And it's still way less

00:40:33,886 --> 00:40:35,286
than what Barbara and Mark
are asking for.

00:40:35,286 --> 00:40:38,096
They're so greedy.

00:40:38,096 --> 00:40:40,886
Ooh! So, grandmas...
(Daymond) I think--
Yeah, I think, uh...

00:40:40,886 --> 00:40:42,236
grandmas, you--
That might sweeten the deal.

00:40:42,236 --> 00:40:46,246
Uh, if you have two sharks
here for less percentage.

00:40:46,246 --> 00:40:48,796
So, grandmas,
Kevin and Daymond,

00:40:48,796 --> 00:40:50,096
or Mark and Barbara?

00:40:50,096 --> 00:40:51,216
The sweet deal,
or the yuck mouths?

00:40:53,986 --> 00:40:56,086
The vindictive deal,
or the honest deal?

00:40:56,086 --> 00:40:57,966
We know.
We know.

00:40:57,966 --> 00:41:00,146
Oh, you do? Wow.

00:41:00,146 --> 00:41:02,796
(Daymond)
I've decided that--
(Kevin) What--

00:41:02,796 --> 00:41:05,146
I've decided that I-I'm
dropping my partner already...

00:41:05,146 --> 00:41:07,236
Oh.

00:41:07,236 --> 00:41:09,046
And I'm going down--
Whoa, everything
changes in the tank!

00:41:09,046 --> 00:41:12,066
And I'm going down
to 25% for $250,000.

00:41:12,066 --> 00:41:13,266
(Robert and Mark) WHOA!
Whoa!

00:41:13,266 --> 00:41:16,286
Daymond, what happened there?
Your offer is $250,000

00:41:16,286 --> 00:41:18,016
for 25%...
(Kevin) Whoa.

00:41:18,016 --> 00:41:19,886
But you, just like Barbara,

00:41:19,886 --> 00:41:21,066
are dumping Kevin to the curb.

00:41:21,066 --> 00:41:22,796
I'm dumping Kevin.
The only reason why

00:41:22,796 --> 00:41:25,886
is because I feel this
Barbara crap growing on them,

00:41:25,886 --> 00:41:28,236
and I want to make sure
that they don't make

00:41:28,236 --> 00:41:30,146
the wrong decision.

00:41:30,146 --> 00:41:32,216
So, what are you gonna do?

00:41:40,866 --> 00:41:41,966
You can tell.
Okay.

00:41:41,966 --> 00:41:43,936
We're gonna go
with Barbara and Mark.

00:41:43,936 --> 00:41:45,146
Ahh!
Good decision.

00:41:45,146 --> 00:41:47,846
Yes!
Thank you so much.

00:41:47,846 --> 00:41:50,836
Thank you.
Smart people.
You picked the good people.

00:41:50,836 --> 00:41:52,096
I never liked grandmothers.

00:41:52,096 --> 00:41:54,266
Don't be mean to grandma.
Bye.

00:41:54,266 --> 00:41:56,036
Thanks, ladies.
Bye.

00:41:56,036 --> 00:41:57,886
(Charlotte)
We so appreciate them all,

00:41:57,886 --> 00:42:00,896
but we just really felt
the Barbara/Mark combination,

00:42:00,896 --> 00:42:03,946
for our personality,
was probably gonna be the best.

00:42:03,946 --> 00:42:05,146
Business-wise,

00:42:05,146 --> 00:42:07,286
a different decision
might be good,

00:42:07,286 --> 00:42:10,216
but personality-wise,
we will...

00:42:10,216 --> 00:42:12,936
be happy.
Kill it together.
(laughs)

00:42:12,936 --> 00:42:15,116
listen, I can go to bed
knowing I helped granny.

00:42:15,116 --> 00:42:17,146
Talk about judging a book
by its cover.

00:42:17,146 --> 00:42:18,216
They're hustlers.

00:42:18,216 --> 00:42:21,046
This is something
that Barbara will enjoy.

00:42:21,046 --> 00:42:22,816
They will love to get
on the phone with her

00:42:22,816 --> 00:42:24,946
and hear her ramble about
her cockamamie stories

00:42:24,946 --> 00:42:26,916
for, like, two weeks.
(laughs)

00:42:26,916 --> 00:42:30,216
I loved the grandmas.
I love the gramas, too,
and I hate--UGH!

00:42:30,216 --> 00:42:34,236
♪♪♪

